"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/719"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"719"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84595"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1266"},{"type":"tags","id":"2118"},{"type":"tags","id":"3189"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"},{"type":"tags","id":"3390"},{"type":"tags","id":"3463"},{"type":"tags","id":"3696"},{"type":"tags","id":"4061"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"9078"},{"type":"tags","id":"9528"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1278"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1334"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18364"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35621"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102137","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/102137"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 53-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a seven-day history of right upper abdominal pain radiating to the shoulder. She reports nausea and loose stools over the past week, with fever and chills developing the previous day. She has now become irritable and drowsy. Her medical history includes known gallstones. She does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell and confused. Her pulse rate is 120/min, blood pressure 70/50 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 94% on room air, and temperature 39.0\u00b0C. There is mild right upper quadrant tenderness. Investigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhite cell count 18 \u00a0x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E /L (4.0-11.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECRP 180 mg/L (\u0026lt;5)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBilirubin 42 \u00b5mol/L (1-24)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGGT 305 IU/L (\u0026lt;60)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EALP 233 U/L (30-110)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EALT 350 U/L (\u0026lt;55)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAST 197 U/L (\u0026lt;45)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn ultrasound confirms biliary dilatation with evidence of gallstones but no findings of cholecystitis or marked site of obstruction.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management after initial resuscitation and antibiotic administration?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Urgent magnetic resonance cholangiopancreatography (MRCP)","Laparotomy with bile duct exploration","Endoscopic retrograde cholangiopancreatography (ERCP)","Laparoscopic cholecystectomy with intraoperative cholangiogram","Percutaneous transhepatic bile duct drainage"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a classical description of acute cholangitis, a potentially life-threatening condition characterised by infection of the biliary system. The patient\u0027s presentation with Charcot\u0027s triad (right upper quadrant pain, fever, and jaundice - as indicated by the raised bilirubin) along with confusion (part of Reynolds\u0027 pentad) suggests severe cholangitis with organ dysfunction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter initial resuscitation with intravenous fluids, blood cultures, and broad-spectrum antibiotics, the priority in management is biliary decompression. \u003Cstrong\u003EEndoscopic retrograde cholangiopancreatography (ERCP)\u003C/strong\u003E is the preferred method for biliary drainage in acute cholangitis. It is less invasive than surgical options and allows for both diagnostic evaluation and therapeutic intervention in the same procedure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrgent magnetic resonance cholangiopancreatography (MRCP)\u003C/strong\u003E can provide detailed imaging of the biliary tree, but it does not offer therapeutic options for drainage. In this acute setting, where the diagnosis is clear and immediate drainage is needed, MRCP would unnecessarily delay definitive treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELaparotomy with bile duct exploration\u003C/strong\u003E is an invasive procedure that carries significant risks, especially in a septic patient. It would be considered only if less invasive methods of biliary drainage are unsuccessful or unavailable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELaparoscopic cholecystectomy with intraoperative cholangiogram\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate as the initial management for acute cholangitis. The patient needs urgent biliary decompression before any definitive surgical management of gallstones can be considered.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPercutaneous transhepatic bile duct drainage\u003C/strong\u003E is an alternative method for biliary decompression when ERCP is not feasible or has failed. However, it is generally considered second-line to ERCP due to its more invasive nature and higher risk of complications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe Tokyo Guidelines, published by the Japanese Society of Hepato-Biliary-Pancreatic Surgery, provide a framework for diagnosing and managing acute cholangitis based on severity. In cases of moderate to severe cholangitis with organ dysfunction, as seen in this patient, urgent biliary drainage is necessary. ERCP is recommended as the first-line approach for biliary decompression due to its effectiveness and relatively low invasiveness.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter successful biliary drainage and resolution of the acute infection, the patient may require further treatment for the underlying gallstone disease, such as elective laparoscopic cholecystectomy. However, the immediate priority is to address the acute cholangitis and sepsis through prompt biliary decompression via ERCP.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Prompt bile duct drainage is essential in the management of stone-related biliary sepsis.","Endoscopic retrograde cholangiopancreatography (ERCP) is the preferred method for biliary decompression in acute cholangitis.","The Tokyo Guidelines provide a framework for diagnosing and managing acute cholangitis based on severity."],"references":["Miura F, Okamoto K, Takada T, Strasberg SM, Asbun HJ, Pitt HA, et al. Tokyo Guidelines 2018: initial management of acute biliary infection and flowchart for acute cholangitis. J Hepatobiliary Pancreat Sci. 2018 Jan;25(1):31-40. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28941329/","Ahmed M. Acute cholangitis - an update. World J Gastrointest Pathophysiol. 2018 Feb 15;9(1):1-7. Available at: https://doi.org/10.4291/wjgp.v9.i1.1","Kiriyama S, Takada T, Strasberg SM, Solomkin JS, Mayumi T, Pitt HA, et al. TG13 guidelines for diagnosis and severity grading of acute cholangitis (with videos). J Hepatobiliary Pancreat Sci. 2013 Jan;20(1):24-34. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/23307001/","Buyukasik K, Toros AB, Bektas H, et al. Diagnostic and therapeutic value of ERCP in acute cholangitis. ISRN Gastroenterol. 2013;2013:191729. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC3753744/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84595"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"719"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84595","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/84595"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-08T23:08:39+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-08T23:09:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"719"}},